WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.530 --> 00:00:02.630
<v ->Ports and protocols.</v>

2
00:00:02.630 --> 00:00:04.280
Now I'm going to apologize in advance

3
00:00:04.280 --> 00:00:06.540
because this is a lengthy lecture,

4
00:00:06.540 --> 00:00:08.540
and it's probably you're going to want to go through

5
00:00:08.540 --> 00:00:09.740
two or three times,

6
00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:12.190
because the information in this lecture

7
00:00:12.190 --> 00:00:14.780
is going to make up a good percentage of your test.

8
00:00:14.780 --> 00:00:18.770
In fact, I'd probably say five to 10% of your test questions

9
00:00:18.770 --> 00:00:21.450
could come from this lecture alone,

10
00:00:21.450 --> 00:00:24.410
and that's why it's really important to really learn it.

11
00:00:24.410 --> 00:00:27.270
So if there's any of these lectures you're going to memorize,

12
00:00:27.270 --> 00:00:29.690
this is going to be the one for you.

13
00:00:29.690 --> 00:00:32.430
So, I'm going to go through each of the different ports

14
00:00:32.430 --> 00:00:34.950
and protocols that you need to be aware of,

15
00:00:34.950 --> 00:00:37.730
and each one has a specified port number.

16
00:00:37.730 --> 00:00:39.090
So let's go ahead and gets tarted,

17
00:00:39.090 --> 00:00:41.400
and I want to tell you what you need to remember.

18
00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:45.890
So here's an example, File Transfer Protocol, or FTP.

19
00:00:45.890 --> 00:00:48.860
It operates on ports 20 and 21.

20
00:00:48.860 --> 00:00:51.560
So what do you need to know about FTP for the exam?

21
00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:55.310
Well, you should know FTP means File Transfer Protocol.

22
00:00:55.310 --> 00:00:56.970
You should know the port number,

23
00:00:56.970 --> 00:00:59.610
and you should know basically what it does.

24
00:00:59.610 --> 00:01:01.280
In the case of File Transfer Protocol,

25
00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:03.170
it's going to allow you to transfer files

26
00:01:03.170 --> 00:01:06.540
between a client and a server on a computer network.

27
00:01:06.540 --> 00:01:08.370
This is an unsecure method,

28
00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:10.810
and data is transmitted in the clear,

29
00:01:10.810 --> 00:01:12.580
meaning there is no encryption.

30
00:01:12.580 --> 00:01:15.250
And so, it is not really safe to use anymore,

31
00:01:15.250 --> 00:01:17.400
and we don't really use File Transfer Protocol

32
00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:21.590
for anything that should be confidential or encrypted.

33
00:01:21.590 --> 00:01:25.620
So, for the exam, File Transfer Protocol transfers files

34
00:01:25.620 --> 00:01:27.650
over ports 20 and 21.

35
00:01:28.520 --> 00:01:31.890
The next one we have is Secure Shell, or SSH,

36
00:01:31.890 --> 00:01:34.770
and this operates on port 22.

37
00:01:34.770 --> 00:01:36.370
What does SSH do?

38
00:01:36.370 --> 00:01:39.300
Well, it allows you to take remote control

39
00:01:39.300 --> 00:01:42.410
of another computer using a command shell.

40
00:01:42.410 --> 00:01:45.490
It is best know for this remove logon capability,

41
00:01:45.490 --> 00:01:46.760
and it is going to give you

42
00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:49.170
a cryptographic network protocol here,

43
00:01:49.170 --> 00:01:51.010
which means it does use encryption

44
00:01:51.010 --> 00:01:54.210
so it is safe to use even over an unsecured network

45
00:01:54.210 --> 00:01:55.420
like the internet.

46
00:01:55.420 --> 00:01:57.620
So, for example, if I want to go and change

47
00:01:57.620 --> 00:01:59.710
the configure of my web server,

48
00:01:59.710 --> 00:02:03.950
I can actually login through SSH from my house in Maryland

49
00:02:03.950 --> 00:02:07.020
to my file server sitting in California

50
00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:09.230
over the internet using SSH,

51
00:02:09.230 --> 00:02:11.350
and be assured that it's secure

52
00:02:11.350 --> 00:02:13.950
because I have encryption on both ends of that.

53
00:02:13.950 --> 00:02:17.460
So, Secure Shell, SSH, port 22,

54
00:02:17.460 --> 00:02:20.590
secure remote control of another machine,

55
00:02:20.590 --> 00:02:22.540
using a text-based environment.

56
00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:26.340
The next one we have is Secure Shell

57
00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:29.500
File Transfer Protocol, or SFTP.

58
00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:32.320
And this is another way to do file transfer

59
00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:33.730
and do it securely.

60
00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:35.460
It's going to operate on port 22,

61
00:02:35.460 --> 00:02:37.850
the same port that we use for SSH,

62
00:02:37.850 --> 00:02:40.930
because, honestly, all it's doing is tunneling

63
00:02:40.930 --> 00:02:44.620
the FTP protocol through SSH

64
00:02:44.620 --> 00:02:46.530
to give it that file transfer,

65
00:02:46.530 --> 00:02:49.280
using an encrypted method to keep it secure.

66
00:02:50.510 --> 00:02:52.310
Next, we have Telnet,

67
00:02:52.310 --> 00:02:54.820
and it works a lot like the way SSH does.

68
00:02:54.820 --> 00:02:58.810
In fact, Telnet came out many years before SSH.

69
00:02:58.810 --> 00:03:01.380
The problem with Telnet is it is insecure.

70
00:03:01.380 --> 00:03:04.050
It provides bio directional, interactive,

71
00:03:04.050 --> 00:03:06.170
text-oriented communication

72
00:03:06.170 --> 00:03:08.500
using a virtual terminal connection.

73
00:03:08.500 --> 00:03:10.220
That's a whole lot of words to say

74
00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:13.100
remote access via the command prompt, okay?

75
00:03:13.100 --> 00:03:15.880
The problem is everything is sent in the clear.

76
00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:18.589
Just like FTP is insecure for that reason, so is Telnet.

77
00:03:18.589 --> 00:03:21.450
You should never use Telnet

78
00:03:21.450 --> 00:03:23.680
over an insecure network like the internet,

79
00:03:23.680 --> 00:03:26.320
because people can read your username, password,

80
00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:28.710
and every other command that you type in.

81
00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:30.080
Just don't do it.

82
00:03:31.310 --> 00:03:34.130
Next, we have the Simple Mail Transfer Protocol,

83
00:03:34.130 --> 00:03:36.210
or SMTP.

84
00:03:36.210 --> 00:03:38.560
This operates on port 25.

85
00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:40.070
It is the internet standard

86
00:03:40.070 --> 00:03:42.130
for sending electronic messages.

87
00:03:42.130 --> 00:03:44.930
And so, it was actually founded back with RFC

88
00:03:44.930 --> 00:03:47.380
or Request for Comments 821

89
00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:49.810
back in 1982.

90
00:03:49.810 --> 00:03:53.110
And back in 2008, the current version came out,

91
00:03:53.110 --> 00:03:56.210
which uses RFC 5321.

92
00:03:56.210 --> 00:03:58.330
Now, do you need to know these RFCs?

93
00:03:58.330 --> 00:04:00.350
No, don't worry about it.

94
00:04:00.350 --> 00:04:01.940
That's only here for you to give an idea

95
00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:04.050
of just how long we've been using this stuff,

96
00:04:04.050 --> 00:04:06.510
from 1982 all the way to 2008,

97
00:04:06.510 --> 00:04:09.300
and now here in 2018.

98
00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:13.660
When you hear SMTP, I want you to think of send mail.

99
00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:17.450
I'm sending mail out and using port 25.

100
00:04:17.450 --> 00:04:19.960
Domain Name Service, or DNS,

101
00:04:19.960 --> 00:04:22.250
which is port 53.

102
00:04:22.250 --> 00:04:24.780
DNS is what gives us a hierarchical

103
00:04:24.780 --> 00:04:26.760
decentralized naming system

104
00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:29.670
for computers, services, and other resources

105
00:04:29.670 --> 00:04:32.420
connected private networks and the internet.

106
00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:36.030
This is going to convert domain names to IP addresses.

107
00:04:36.030 --> 00:04:39.790
So for example, if you go to diontraining.com,

108
00:04:39.790 --> 00:04:41.370
that's a lot easier to remember

109
00:04:41.370 --> 00:04:46.000
than 66.12.54.85.

110
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:47.120
That'll be hard to remember.

111
00:04:47.120 --> 00:04:50.420
It's easier to remember diontraining.com, right?

112
00:04:50.420 --> 00:04:52.160
Or wikipedia.org,

113
00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:53.240
and it will go through,

114
00:04:53.240 --> 00:04:56.140
and we'll talk more about DNS in a future lecture.

115
00:04:56.140 --> 00:04:58.630
The next one we have is DHCP,

116
00:04:58.630 --> 00:05:01.310
or Dynamic Host Control Protocol,

117
00:05:01.310 --> 00:05:05.290
and this operates on ports 67 and 68.

118
00:05:05.290 --> 00:05:09.090
DHCP servers automatically assign IP addresses

119
00:05:09.090 --> 00:05:11.610
and other network configuration parameters

120
00:05:11.610 --> 00:05:13.420
to your network clients.

121
00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:15.420
This is going to allow your computers

122
00:05:15.420 --> 00:05:18.940
to get IP addresses and network parameters automatically,

123
00:05:18.940 --> 00:05:21.110
which is really, really awesome,

124
00:05:21.110 --> 00:05:23.210
and makes your life as a network administrator

125
00:05:23.210 --> 00:05:25.020
much, much easier.

126
00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:27.390
We have a separate lecture on DHCP

127
00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:29.760
where we're going to talk all about the methods

128
00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:31.160
that it uses to get those

129
00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:32.800
between the discover, the offer,

130
00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:34.340
the request, and the acknowledge.

131
00:05:34.340 --> 00:05:35.990
So, just hold on for that.

132
00:05:35.990 --> 00:05:38.170
For right now, I want you to remember

133
00:05:38.170 --> 00:05:39.690
DHCP

134
00:05:39.690 --> 00:05:41.770
is port 67 and 68,

135
00:05:41.770 --> 00:05:44.320
and it automatically assigns IPs.

136
00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:46.120
If you remember those three things right now,

137
00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:47.690
you're good to go.

138
00:05:47.690 --> 00:05:52.270
The next one we have is Trivial File Transfer, or TFTP,

139
00:05:52.270 --> 00:05:54.820
which operates on port 69.

140
00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:57.400
This is going to transmit files in both directions

141
00:05:57.400 --> 00:05:59.640
of a client server application.

142
00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:02.160
It's used for booting things like operating systems

143
00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:03.860
off a network file server,

144
00:06:03.860 --> 00:06:06.120
and it doesn't provide any authentication

145
00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:07.730
or directory visibility.

146
00:06:07.730 --> 00:06:10.970
It's a very stripped down version of FTP.

147
00:06:10.970 --> 00:06:12.330
Where do we use this?

148
00:06:12.330 --> 00:06:14.390
Usually in sending configuration files

149
00:06:14.390 --> 00:06:16.150
or requesting configuration files

150
00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:17.890
from routers and switches,

151
00:06:17.890 --> 00:06:20.340
or, like I said, booting up an operating system

152
00:06:20.340 --> 00:06:21.670
off a network drive.

153
00:06:22.840 --> 00:06:27.110
Next, we have Hyper Text Transfer Protocol, or HTTP.

154
00:06:27.110 --> 00:06:29.330
This operates on port 80.

155
00:06:29.330 --> 00:06:31.710
This is the foundation of data communication

156
00:06:31.710 --> 00:06:33.530
for the world wide web.

157
00:06:33.530 --> 00:06:37.470
It's designed for collaborative and hyper media presentation

158
00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:39.580
across many devices.

159
00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:41.290
When you hear port 80,

160
00:06:41.290 --> 00:06:43.600
I want you to think of HTTP,

161
00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:46.460
which is unsecured web browsing.

162
00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:49.820
We'll get to the secured web browsing in a little bit.

163
00:06:49.820 --> 00:06:53.160
The next one we have is Post Office Protocol Version Three,

164
00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:54.760
or POP3.

165
00:06:54.760 --> 00:06:58.130
This is port one, one, zero, or 110.

166
00:06:58.130 --> 00:07:00.220
It is used by local email clients

167
00:07:00.220 --> 00:07:02.870
to retrieve email from a remote server

168
00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:05.860
over a TCP/IP connection.

169
00:07:05.860 --> 00:07:08.380
When you hear POP3, I want you to think of

170
00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:09.730
downloading email,

171
00:07:09.730 --> 00:07:11.330
because that's what it's for.

172
00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:17.100
Next, we have Network Time Protocol, or NTP.

173
00:07:17.100 --> 00:07:19.370
NTP operates on port 123.

174
00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:23.070
Now, I like that because it's easy to remember right?

175
00:07:23.070 --> 00:07:25.260
Think of it like you're counting, one, two, three,

176
00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:29.040
just like I'm watching time fly, Network Time Protocol.

177
00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:31.050
Network Time Protocol is going to provide you

178
00:07:31.050 --> 00:07:32.460
a clock synchronization

179
00:07:32.460 --> 00:07:34.350
between different computer systems

180
00:07:34.350 --> 00:07:37.860
over packet-switched variable latency data networks.

181
00:07:37.860 --> 00:07:39.900
And it was created back in 1985,

182
00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:43.440
and it is one of the oldest internet protocols in use today.

183
00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:46.580
NTP is useful to be able to sync up our times.

184
00:07:46.580 --> 00:07:49.490
And in fact, your computer uses NTP all the time,

185
00:07:49.490 --> 00:07:50.840
whether you knew it or not.

186
00:07:52.090 --> 00:07:53.850
Next, we have NetBIOS,

187
00:07:53.850 --> 00:07:56.930
which is on port 139.

188
00:07:56.930 --> 00:08:00.720
NetBIOS is the Network Basic Input/Output System.

189
00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:02.500
And it provides a service for allowing

190
00:08:02.500 --> 00:08:04.960
applications on a separate computer

191
00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:07.570
to communicate over a local area network

192
00:08:07.570 --> 00:08:09.690
to share files and printers.

193
00:08:09.690 --> 00:08:13.000
If you use file or printer sharing in a Windows network,

194
00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.170
your port 139 is probably open,

195
00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:16.870
because you're using that BIOS.

196
00:08:18.090 --> 00:08:21.040
Next, we have the Internet Mail Application Protocol,

197
00:08:21.040 --> 00:08:22.060
or IMAP,

198
00:08:22.060 --> 00:08:25.330
and it operates on port 143.

199
00:08:25.330 --> 00:08:27.080
It's going to provide email clients

200
00:08:27.080 --> 00:08:30.000
the ability to retrieve email messages from a mail server

201
00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.800
over a TCP/IP connection.

202
00:08:32.800 --> 00:08:35.670
It's going to allow the end user to view and manipulate

203
00:08:35.670 --> 00:08:37.330
the messages as if they were stored

204
00:08:37.330 --> 00:08:38.900
locally on their machine.

205
00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:42.510
So with POP3, if I log in from my laptop and my tablet,

206
00:08:42.510 --> 00:08:45.070
it would show unread on one and read on the other.

207
00:08:45.070 --> 00:08:47.340
With IMAP, it keeps them all synchronized,

208
00:08:47.340 --> 00:08:50.180
so it is much better for modern communication.

209
00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:55.220
Simple Network Management Protocol, or SNMP,

210
00:08:55.220 --> 00:08:58.270
which operates on port 161.

211
00:08:58.270 --> 00:09:00.230
This is going to provide you a collection

212
00:09:00.230 --> 00:09:02.020
and organization of information

213
00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:04.670
about the managed devices on IP networks,

214
00:09:04.670 --> 00:09:08.060
such as your routers and your switches and other devices.

215
00:09:08.060 --> 00:09:09.630
It can modify the information

216
00:09:09.630 --> 00:09:11.510
by changing the device's behavior,

217
00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:14.940
and it is commonly used in these network devices.

218
00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:18.110
We will talk about SNMP much later in this course

219
00:09:18.110 --> 00:09:19.660
in it's own lecture as well,

220
00:09:19.660 --> 00:09:21.960
because it is important to network management.

221
00:09:22.820 --> 00:09:25.680
Next, we have the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol,

222
00:09:25.680 --> 00:09:26.680
or LDAP,

223
00:09:26.680 --> 00:09:28.060
L-D-A-P,

224
00:09:28.060 --> 00:09:31.240
and it operates on port 389.

225
00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:34.780
This is an open, vendor-neutral, industry standard

226
00:09:34.780 --> 00:09:37.630
for accessing and maintaining distributed

227
00:09:37.630 --> 00:09:40.020
directory information services.

228
00:09:40.020 --> 00:09:44.000
So, LDAP and active directory both will use this port.

229
00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:45.960
So when you go to your email program

230
00:09:45.960 --> 00:09:47.860
like Microsoft Outlook at work,

231
00:09:47.860 --> 00:09:50.940
and you try to look up somebody's name in the address book,

232
00:09:50.940 --> 00:09:52.420
you're actually using LDAP.

233
00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:55.260
Now we're back to secure web browsing,

234
00:09:55.260 --> 00:09:58.750
which is HTTPS, for secure.

235
00:09:58.750 --> 00:10:01.570
This is going to use TLS or SSL

236
00:10:01.570 --> 00:10:02.970
to encrypt your connection,

237
00:10:02.970 --> 00:10:05.580
and allow you to do thins like e-commerce

238
00:10:05.580 --> 00:10:08.910
and password login over the web securely.

239
00:10:08.910 --> 00:10:11.130
It's designed to add the security layer

240
00:10:11.130 --> 00:10:13.620
to the insecure HTTP protocol.

241
00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:16.640
HTTPS operates on port 443.

242
00:10:19.650 --> 00:10:21.810
Next, we have Server Message Block,

243
00:10:21.810 --> 00:10:24.370
which is SMB port 445.

244
00:10:25.310 --> 00:10:26.470
Server Message Block

245
00:10:26.470 --> 00:10:29.420
is going to provide you with shared access to files,

246
00:10:29.420 --> 00:10:31.750
printers, and other types of communication

247
00:10:31.750 --> 00:10:33.770
between devices on the network.

248
00:10:33.770 --> 00:10:38.370
It operates a lot of the times with NetBios at port 139

249
00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:40.000
in conjunction with each other,

250
00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.010
where NetBIOS does the authentication,

251
00:10:42.010 --> 00:10:44.330
and Server Message Block actually handles

252
00:10:44.330 --> 00:10:46.770
passing out those files for you.

253
00:10:46.770 --> 00:10:48.960
Next, we have LDAP secure.

254
00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:50.400
Just like most things,

255
00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:52.620
we have a secure and unsecure version.

256
00:10:52.620 --> 00:10:55.950
An LDAP secure or L-D-A-P-S

257
00:10:55.950 --> 00:10:58.220
is port 636.

258
00:10:58.220 --> 00:11:01.260
It again is going to operate just like LDAP did,

259
00:11:01.260 --> 00:11:03.030
Active Directory can operate on it,

260
00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:05.080
and it's going to be that directory structure.

261
00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:08.260
Just here, we're going to add TLS or SSL,

262
00:11:08.260 --> 00:11:11.120
and add that encryption layer to make it more secure.

263
00:11:11.120 --> 00:11:15.680
And next, we have the remote desktop protocol or RDP.

264
00:11:15.680 --> 00:11:18.480
It operates on port 3389.

265
00:11:18.480 --> 00:11:19.500
Now, be careful here,

266
00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:22.180
because you'll notice 3389

267
00:11:22.180 --> 00:11:24.440
looks a lot like 389

268
00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:25.590
to use for LDAP,

269
00:11:25.590 --> 00:11:28.491
and students will commonly mix these two up.

270
00:11:28.491 --> 00:11:32.640
RDP is a proprietary protocol developed by Microsoft,

271
00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:35.830
and it allows the user to a have a graphical interface,

272
00:11:35.830 --> 00:11:38.190
and be able to remotely control another computer

273
00:11:38.190 --> 00:11:39.270
over the network.

274
00:11:39.270 --> 00:11:41.270
So, with SSH and Telnet,

275
00:11:41.270 --> 00:11:44.400
we have this command line text-based information.

276
00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:48.170
But with RDP, I actually can look at this thing remotely.

277
00:11:48.170 --> 00:11:50.560
As you can see here, I have an Android phone

278
00:11:50.560 --> 00:11:54.130
that's actually RDP in through the web browser,

279
00:11:54.130 --> 00:11:56.120
and is able to see this Windows machine

280
00:11:56.120 --> 00:11:57.910
and control it remotely.

281
00:11:57.910 --> 00:12:00.560
This allows users with RDP client software

282
00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:03.660
to be able to access their computer from anywhere they are,

283
00:12:03.660 --> 00:12:05.790
over the internet or inside the network,

284
00:12:05.790 --> 00:12:07.920
over port 3389.

285
00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.990
Next, we have the Session Initiation Protocol, or SIP.

286
00:12:12.990 --> 00:12:16.370
And SIP operates on port 5060

287
00:12:16.370 --> 00:12:18.510
and 5061.

288
00:12:18.510 --> 00:12:20.250
This is going to provide the signaling

289
00:12:20.250 --> 00:12:22.630
and controlling media communication sessions

290
00:12:22.630 --> 00:12:24.190
for applications.

291
00:12:24.190 --> 00:12:27.790
This is used in VOIP, video calls, and voice calls,

292
00:12:27.790 --> 00:12:29.440
as well as instant messaging.

293
00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:31.930
And so, if you're using something like Skype

294
00:12:31.930 --> 00:12:34.070
or a VOIP service in your work,

295
00:12:34.070 --> 00:12:35.790
This is probably using SIP

296
00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:37.750
to initiate that communication.

297
00:12:39.240 --> 00:12:41.990
Now, that was a lot of information.

298
00:12:41.990 --> 00:12:45.730
And the next two slides I have for you are charts.

299
00:12:45.730 --> 00:12:48.530
So if you print out these two charts and you memorize them,

300
00:12:48.530 --> 00:12:50.310
you're going to be good for testing.

301
00:12:50.310 --> 00:12:52.730
This is one of those things that I would data dump

302
00:12:52.730 --> 00:12:54.240
when you sit down at the exam

303
00:12:54.240 --> 00:12:56.330
on that piece of paper they gave you.

304
00:12:56.330 --> 00:12:59.080
This is going to have all of your services,

305
00:12:59.080 --> 00:13:01.110
a short description of what they are,

306
00:13:01.110 --> 00:13:02.340
and the port number.

307
00:13:02.340 --> 00:13:06.120
And you can see here, going from FTP down to POP3

308
00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:08.230
is ports 20 through 110.

309
00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:09.700
And on the next slide,

310
00:13:09.700 --> 00:13:11.470
I have NTP through SIP,

311
00:13:11.470 --> 00:13:15.810
which is ports 123 down to 5061.

312
00:13:15.810 --> 00:13:18.040
If you can remember both of these slides,

